: ''Big Pharma may also refer to the [[pharmaceutical lobby]].'' {{Infobox book | name = Big Pharma | image = Big Pharma (Jacky Law book).jpg | author = Jacky Law | country = UK | genre = Science writing, medicine, investigative journalism | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | language = | series = | subject = [[Pharmaceutical industry]] | publisher = Constable (UK) | publisher2 = Carroll & Graf (US) | pub_date = 16 January 2006 | pages = 256 | isbn = 978-1845291396 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''Big Pharma: How the World's Biggest Drug Companies Control Illness''''' is a 2006 book by British journalist Jacky Law.<!--Note: most of the images of the cover available online say the subtitle is "how the world's biggest drug companies market illness," but the reviewers say "control illness."--> The book examines how major [[pharmaceutical companies]] determine which [[health care]] problems are publicised and researched.<ref name=bmj06>{{cite journal |title=Big Pharma: How the World's Biggest Drug Companies Control Illness |author=Ike Iheanacho |date=18 March 2006 |volume=332 |issue=7542 |page=672 |work=BMJ |doi=10.1136/bmj.332.7542.672 |pmc=1403244}}</ref>
Outlining the history of the [[pharmaceutical industry]], Law identifies what she says is the failure of a regulatory framework that assumes pharmaceutical companies always produce worthwhile products that society will want.<ref name=bmj06/>
Law has written about healthcare for 25 years, seven of them as associate editor of ''Scrip Magazine'', a monthly magazine for the drugs industry.<ref name=nhf>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenhf.com/page.php?id=33 |title=Big Pharma: How the World's Biggest Drug Companies Control Illness |author= |date=2006 |work=National Health Federation |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502144831/http://www.thenhf.com/page.php?id=33 |archivedate=2012-05-02 |df= }}</ref>
