{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}} {{Use Australian English|date=February 2014}} [[File:CP de la Motte - 'With the Aurora', 1919.png|thumb|CP de la Motte - "Officers of the Aurora", from [https://archive.org/details/withaurorainanta00davi '' With the "Aurora" in the Antarctic, 1911-1914''] (1919).]] '''Clarence Petersen de la Motte''' (born 1892, date of death unknown), commonly '''C. P. de la Motte''', was a sailor originally from [[Bulli, New South Wales]]. During his early career, he served aboard the New Zealand [[barque]] ''Northern Chief'' and the [[steamship]] ''Warrimoo''.<ref name="Bio">{{cite web |url= http://www.mawsonshuts.aq/voyages/people-of-aurora/clarence-petersen-de-la-motte.html |title= People of Aurora: Clarence Petersen de la Motte |work= Australian Antarctic Division |publisher= [[Australian Antarctic Division]] |accessdate= 2011-03-19}}</ref> From 1911 to 1914, during the [[Australasian Antarctic Expedition]], he served as Third Officer aboard the [[SY Aurora|SY ''Aurora'']], under [[John King Davis]].<ref name="Davis p. 170">{{Citation |author= Davis, John King|title= With the "Aurora" in the Antarctic, 1911-1914|origyear=|year=1919|publisher=A. Melrose |location=London |isbn=|page=170}}</ref><ref name="Mawson p. 8">{{Citation |author= Mawson, Douglas|title= The home of the blizzard: the story of the Australasian Antarctic Expedition, 1911-1914|origyear=1915|year=1996|publisher=Wakefield Press |location=Kent Town, South Australia|isbn= 978-1-86254-377-5|page=8}}</ref> Expedition Commander [[Douglas Mawson]] named [[Cape De la Motte]], in [[George V Land]], after him.<ref name="AADC">{{cite web |url= http://data.aad.gov.au/aadc/gaz/display_name.cfm?gaz_id=280 |title= Cape De La Motte |work= Australian Antarctic Data Centre |publisher= [[Australian Antarctic Division]] |accessdate= 2011-03-19}}</ref> De la Motte joined the ''Aurora'' again in 1916, and served as First Officer during the rescue of the [[Ross Sea party|Ross Sea component]] of the [[Imperial Trans-Antarctic Expedition]], for which he was later awarded the [[Polar Medal]].<ref name="Bio"/>
