'''Hiroshige''' is a [[impact crater|crater]] on [[Mercury (planet)|Mercury]] located at 13 S, 27 W. It is 138&nbsp;km in diameter and was named after [[Andō Hiroshige]].
{{Mercury (planet)}}

[[Category:Impact craters on Mercury]]


{{crater-stub}}
{{Mercury-planet-stub}}

'''John T. Dingle''' is a British biologist and [[rheumatologist]]. He joined the staff of the [[Strangeways Research Laboratory]] in 1959 as a research assistant to then-director [[Honor Fell]], and later himself served as director from 1979 to 1993, taking over the position after the death of [[Michael Abercrombie]].<ref name=dingle>{{cite journal|last1=Dingle|first1=JT|title=Seventy five years of arthritis research at the Strangeways Research Laboratory: 1912-87.|journal=Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases|date=November 1987|volume=46|issue=11|pages=801–3|pmid=3322210|url=http://ard.bmj.com/content/46/11/801.full.pdf|doi=10.1136/ard.46.11.801|pmc=1003395}}</ref><ref name=shils>{{cite book|last1=Shils|first1=Edward|last2=Blacker|first2=Carmen|title=Cambridge women : twelve portraits|date=1995|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge [u.a.]|isbn=9780521483445|edition=1. publ.}}</ref>{{rp|259}} His presence at Strangeways helped to move its research direction toward the original research interests of its founder, [[Thomas Strangeways]], who sought to understand the physiology of [[arthritis]] and other rheumatic diseases, after many years in which the laboratory specialized more narrowly in [[tissue culture]] and [[cell biology]].<ref name=dingle /> Dingle was the president of [[Hughes Hall]] from 1993 to 1998, and is an honorary fellow.<ref name=hughes>{{cite web|title=Fellows and Senior Members: John T. Dingle |url=https://www.hughes.cam.ac.uk/about-us/the-fellowship/?fellow=JohnTDingle |website=Hughes Hall, University of Cambridge |accessdate=15 December 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151211002435/https://www.hughes.cam.ac.uk/about-us/the-fellowship/?fellow=JohnTDingle |archivedate=11 December 2015 |df= }}</ref> He was the founding chairman of the British Connective Tissue Society (now the British Society for Matrix Biology), serving from 1980 to 1987.<ref name=bsmb>{{cite web|last1=Ashhurst|first1=Doreen E.|last2=Bailey|first2=Allen J.|title=The first 25 years|url=http://www.bsmb.ac.uk/articles/documents/THEFIRST25YEARS-BSMBhistorySept2005_000.pdf|website=British Society for Matrix Biology|accessdate=15 December 2015|date=September 2005}}</ref> Among his notable trainees is [[University of California, San Francisco]] cell biologist [[Zena Werb]], who was a [[postdoctoral fellow]] with Dingle and subsequently worked as a research assistant at Strangeways.<ref name=ascb>{{cite web|title=ASCB Profiles|url=http://ascb.org/files/profiles/Zena_Werb.pdf|website=American Society for Cell Biology|accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>

