{{Infobox astronaut | name = Li Qinglong | honorific_suffix = | image = Li Qinglong 2010 Somalia stamp.jpg | image_size = 150px | alt = | caption = | type = | native_name = 李庆龙 | native_name_lang = zh | nationality = | status = | birth_name = | birth_date = August 1962<ref>http://www.astronautix.com/l/liqinglong.html</ref> | birth_place = Dingyuan, Anhui | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coords = | other_names = | occupation = | current_occupation = | previous_occupation = | alma_mater = | rank = | space_time = | selection = | evas = | eva_time = <!-- h m s --> | missions = <!-- or: |mission= --> | insignia = | retirement = <!-- {{end date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | awards = | memorials = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | module = | child = }} '''Li Qinglong''' ({{zh|s=李庆龙|t=李慶龍|p=Lǐ Qìnglóng}}; born August 1962) is a [[People's Republic of China|Chinese]] [[aviator|pilot]] selected as part of the [[Shenzhou spacecraft|Shenzhou program]].
==Biography== Li Qinglong was born in [[Dingyuan County|Dingyuan]], [[Anhui]] province, China. In 1987 he graduated from the [[People's Liberation Army Air Force]] (PLAAF) Missile College and later the PLAAF Flight College. A [[fighter aircraft|fighter]] pilot in the PLAAF, he had accumulated 1230 flight-hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spacefacts.de/bios/international/english/li_qinglong.htm|title=Taikonaut (yuhangyuan) Biography: Li Qinglong|last=Becker|first=Joachim|website=www.spacefacts.de|access-date=2016-12-27}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/l/liqinglong.html|title=Li Qinglong|last=|first=|date=|website=www.astronautix.com|publisher=[[Encyclopedia Astronautica]]|access-date=2016-12-27}}</ref>
In November 1996, he and [[Wu Jie]], started training at the Russian [[Yuri Gagarin Cosmonauts Training Center]]. When they returned to China a year later, they acted as the trainers for the first group of astronauts. In January 2003 it was reported by a [[Hong Kong]] [[newspaper]] that Chen Long would make the first manned Shenzhou flight. Then in March 2003 it was reported that Li Qinglong would make the first manned flight. It was thought that "Chen Long" was a misspell of "Qinglong", a fact confirmed by the newspaper a couple of days before the launch of ''[[Shenzhou 5]]'', which was flown by [[Yang Liwei]].<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/2829349.stm|title=BBC NEWS {{!}} Science/Nature {{!}} China's first astronaut revealed|website=news.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2016-12-27}}</ref>
